## Code Conventions (strictly follow these)

### Java POM Class
- Package: `pages`
- Extends: `BasePage`
- Locator constants: `private static final String CONSTANT_NAME = "selector";`
- Naming: `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` for constants, `camelCase` for methods
- Selector priority: `testId > aria-label > #id > [name='x'] > [placeholder] > .class > xpath`
- Never use `Thread.sleep()` — use Playwright auto-wait
- No assertions inside POM — assertions only in step definitions

```java
package pages;
import com.microsoft.playwright.Page;

public class LoginPage extends BasePage {

    // ── Inputs ──
    private static final String USERNAME_INPUT   = "input[name='username']";
    private static final String PASSWORD_INPUT   = "input[type='password']";

    // ── Buttons ──
    private static final String LOGIN_BUTTON     = "button[type='submit']";

    // ── Messages ──
    private static final String ERROR_MESSAGE    = ".error-message";
    private static final String DASHBOARD_HEADER = "h1.dashboard";

    public LoginPage(Page page) { super(page); }

    // ── Navigation ──
    public void navigateTo() { page.navigate("URL_HERE"); }

    // ── Actions ──
    public void enterUsername(String value) { page.fill(USERNAME_INPUT, value); }
    public void enterPassword(String value) { page.fill(PASSWORD_INPUT, value); }
    public void clickLoginButton()          { page.click(LOGIN_BUTTON); }

    // ── Assertions / Getters ──
    public boolean isDashboardVisible()  { return page.isVisible(DASHBOARD_HEADER); }
    public String  getErrorMessage()     { return page.textContent(ERROR_MESSAGE); }
    public boolean isErrorDisplayed()    { return page.isVisible(ERROR_MESSAGE); }
}
```

### Step Definitions Class
- Package: `stepdefinitions`
- Constructor injection via PicoContainer (no `@Autowired`)
- Instantiate page objects in constructor from `PlaywrightContext`
- `@Before` → log scenario name
- `@After` → take screenshot on failure and attach to report
- Use AssertJ for assertions: `Assertions.assertThat(...)`
- Never put Playwright locators directly in step defs — always delegate to page object

```java
package stepdefinitions;
import io.cucumber.java.en.*;
import io.cucumber.java.Before;
import io.cucumber.java.After;
import io.cucumber.java.Scenario;
import pages.LoginPage;
import context.PlaywrightContext;
import org.assertj.core.api.Assertions;

public class LoginSteps {

    private final LoginPage loginPage;

    public LoginSteps(PlaywrightContext context) {
        this.loginPage = new LoginPage(context.getPage());
    }

    @Before
    public void setUp(Scenario scenario) {
        System.out.println("▶ Starting: " + scenario.getName());
    }

    @After
    public void tearDown(Scenario scenario) {
        if (scenario.isFailed()) {
            byte[] screenshot = loginPage.getPage().screenshot();
            scenario.attach(screenshot, "image/png", scenario.getName());
        }
    }

    @Given("the user is on the login page")
    public void userIsOnLoginPage() {
        loginPage.navigateTo();
    }

    @When("the user enters username {string} and password {string}")
    public void userEntersCredentials(String username, String password) {
        loginPage.enterUsername(username);
        loginPage.enterPassword(password);
    }

    @When("the user clicks the login button")
    public void userClicksLoginButton() {
        loginPage.clickLoginButton();
    }

    @Then("the user should be redirected to the dashboard")
    public void userShouldSeeDashboard() {
        Assertions.assertThat(loginPage.isDashboardVisible()).isTrue();
    }

    @Then("an error message {string} should be displayed")
    public void errorMessageShouldBeDisplayed(String expectedMsg) {
        Assertions.assertThat(loginPage.isErrorDisplayed()).isTrue();
        Assertions.assertThat(loginPage.getErrorMessage()).contains(expectedMsg);
    }
}
```

### Feature File
- Location: `src/test/resources/features/`
- Tags: `@smoke`, `@regression`, `@positive`, `@negative`, `@<feature-name>`
- Use `Background:` for steps that repeat in every scenario
- Use `Scenario Outline:` + `Examples:` when same flow runs with different data
- Steps written from user perspective — no technical/UI implementation details
- Present tense: "the user clicks", "the page shows"

```gherkin
@login @smoke
Feature: User Login
  As a registered user
  I want to log into the application
  So that I can access my account

  Background:
    Given the user is on the login page

  @positive
  Scenario: Successful login with valid credentials
    When the user enters username "pavan@test.com" and password "Valid@123"
    And the user clicks the login button
    Then the user should be redirected to the dashboard

  @negative
  Scenario: Login fails with wrong password
    When the user enters username "pavan@test.com" and password "WrongPass"
    And the user clicks the login button
    Then an error message "Invalid credentials" should be displayed

  @datadriven
  Scenario Outline: Login with multiple credential sets
    When the user enters username "<username>" and password "<password>"
    And the user clicks the login button
    Then the page should show "<expected_result>"

    Examples:
      | username          | password   | expected_result |
      | valid@test.com    | Valid@123  | dashboard       |
      | invalid@test.com  | WrongPass  | error message   |
```

